# /etc/abf/repo.d

For each repository to configure, make a directory with same name here.

Example:
	/etc
		/abf
			/repo.d
				/my-public-repo
				/my-private-repo
	
	# mkdir -p /var/abf/repo.d/{my-public-repo,my-private-repo}

Similarly, inside each repository directory, create a 0-byte file for each package to be built.

Example:
	/etc
		/abf
			/repo.d
				/my-public-repo
					yaourt
					dropbox
					aurvote
					package-query
				/my-private-repo
					ttf-adobe-fonts
					ttf-vista-fonts
	
	# touch /var/abf/repo.d/my-public-repo/{yaourt,dropbox,aurvote,package-query}
	# touch /var/abf/repo.d/my-private-repo/{ttf-adobe-fonts,ttf-vista-fonts}

At this stage, these files will be used to
	1. Configure your packages under one or more repository names.
	2. Record timestamps of ABF builds.

Later, these files might also be used to provide functionalities like that in `customizepkg`.
